Glossary of Key Terms

Term	Definition
AWS	Amazon Web Services, the cloud platform that provides the services used in this course.
AWS Management Console	The primary web interface for managing all AWS services. A prerequisite for the course is knowing how to log in and use it.
AWS SageMaker	The preferred platform used in this course for building, training, and hosting machine learning models.
Conditional Statement	A programming construct, such as an if statement in Python, that performs a specific action only if a particular condition is true.
EC2 (Elastic Compute Cloud)	An AWS service for managing virtual machines. Awareness of EC2 is helpful but not required for the course.
ECS (Elastic Container Service)	An AWS service for managing containers. Awareness of ECS is helpful but not required for the course.
For Loop	A programming control flow statement used for iteration. In the context of the course, it is used to loop over elements in a Python list to perform an action on each one.
Inference	The process of using a trained and hosted machine learning model to generate a prediction based on new, previously unseen data.
Iteration	A term for looping over a collection of items, such as the elements in a list, to perform an action on each item.
Linear Learner	A specific, ready-made machine learning algorithm mentioned in the lesson that will be used to solve the house price prediction problem.
List (Python)	A Python data structure used to store a collection of items. Understanding how to define and iterate over lists is a key prerequisite.
ML Algorithm	A ready-made algorithm (e.g., Linear Learner, XGBoost) that is used during the training process to learn patterns from source data.
Model Artifact	The file that is the output of the machine learning training process (e.g., model.tgz). It contains the learned patterns but is not an executable on its own.
Model Hosting	The process of deploying a trained model artifact onto a compute platform (like SageMaker) with supporting code, making it available to receive inference requests.
Prediction	The output generated by a machine learning model during inference. In the course example, this would be the predicted house price.
Python	The programming language used to build and train models in this course. Basic proficiency is a prerequisite.
Route 53	The native Domain Name System (DNS) service in AWS. Awareness of Route 53 is helpful but not essential.
S3 (Simple Storage Service)	An AWS data storage service. For this course, users must be able to create S3 "buckets" and upload/download files to them.
Source Data	The initial dataset used to train a machine learning model. The course uses tabular house price data from London.
Tabular Data	Data organized in a table format with rows and columns, such as the house price data used in the course.
Trained Model	The output of the training process; a model artifact that has learned patterns from the source data and is ready to be hosted for inference.
Training	The core machine learning process where an algorithm learns the relationships and patterns in a source dataset to create a trained model.
